pr_title: Update RecognizeOptions to take only optional params

timeline.bodyText: why do we make a copy of the user-provided options here?
timeline.author: srnagar

timeline.bodyText:
Suggested change
        
          
    

        
      
    
    
      
          
            
                 * @param length The exact length of the data. Size of the file must be less than 50 MB.

timeline.author: srnagar
timeline.diffHunk:
@@ -271,10 +299,12 @@ * {@code Flux} must produce the same data each time it is subscribed to. * *

Code sample

- * {@codesnippet com.azure.ai.formrecognizer.FormRecognizerAsyncClient.beginRecognizeContent#recognizeOptions} + * {@codesnippet com.azure.ai.formrecognizer.FormRecognizerAsyncClient.beginRecognizeContent#Flux-long-recognizeOptions} * - * @param recognizeOptions The configurable {@code RecognizeOptions options} that may be passed when recognizing - * content on a form. + * @param form The data of the form to recognize content information from. + * @param length The exact length of the data. Size of the file must be less than 50 MB.

replies.bodyText: Actually, we should just remove this limit from the javadoc as the limit is controlled by the service and an error will be thrown from the service if the limit exceeds. This allows service to increase or decrease the limit dynamically.
replies.author: srnagar

timeline.bodyText:
subscribe inside another subscribe looks a bit odd. Can we instead use reactor pattern here?
formRecognizerAsyncClient.beginRecognizeReceiptsFromUrl(...)
        .flatMap(recognizePollingOperation -> recognizePollingOperation.getFinalResult())
        .subscribe(recognizedReceipts -> {...});
timeline.author: srnagar

timeline.bodyText: In .NET we call this field ContentType only (without the Form prefix). Are we concerned about consistency in fields names? If formContentType feels more idiomatic to Java, I believe that's not a big concern on the .NET side and can be easily updated.
timeline.author: kinelski

replies.bodyText:
I think we agreed to keep this model named FormContentType.
@kristapratico and @jeremymeng can you confirm what Python and JS have?
replies.author: samvaity

replies.bodyText: The model is called FormContentType as well in .NET. I'm talking about the formContentType, which is simply ContentType in .NET. I know it's private, but since you have the public getFormContentType method, I was wondering whether we should update its name in .NET.
replies.author: kinelski

replies.bodyText: We renamed the type to FormContentType to differentiate from general content type as only a handful content types are supported.
replies.author: jeremymeng

replies.bodyText:
We are all in the same page with the name of the type.
I think what @kinelski is pointing out is the name of the property. Currently .NET, JS, and Python have Content Type for the property name.
replies.author: maririos

replies.bodyText: we don't have this in an option bag in JS.  for parameters it's just contentType
replies.author: jeremymeng

replies.bodyText: I am inclined to keep it consistent with the property name unless we have any strong objections.
replies.author: samvaity

replies.bodyText: I am not against it, although I will like to understand why the deviation from the other languages though
replies.author: maririos

timeline.message: update options to take optional params

timeline.bodyText:
Use forEach() instead or you can also show the reactor pattern here:
formRecognizerAsyncClient.beginRecognizeReceipts(buffer, receipt.length())
     .flatMap(recognizePollingOperation -> recognizePollingOperation.getFinalResult())
     .flatMap(recognizedReceipts -> Flux.fromIterable(recognizedReceipts))
     .subscribe(recognizedReceipt -> {...});
timeline.author: srnagar

replies.bodyText: Yep, I am preparing a follow-up PR for sample and snippets update to follow reactor pattern more!
replies.author: samvaity
